It appears, then, that whereas φωνή is used properly of the voice only, the term was applied also to the tones of musical instrumente. Aristoxenus speaks of φωνὴ ὀργανική τε καὶ ἀνθρωπική (Herm, p. 14 Meib.).

The analysis of articulate sound into its phonetic elements is important to the art of writing, and consequently the various vowel-sounds and consonant-sounds must have been differentiated from very early times, since it was this that led to the invention of writing by letters to take the place of ideographio writing.

Another important principle of division is involved in the distinction between musical and unmusical sounds. This classification concerns chiefly the Scienoe of Music. As Pho- netios disregards all but articulate sounds, so the Scienoe of Music deals only with musical sounds. It should be observed that the line which separatos musical sounds from unmusioal sounds crosses that which separatos articulate and inarticulate sounds. An articulate sound may be either musical or un- mnsical; so may an inarticulate sound. ’

What, then, is meant by musical and unmusical or non- musical? In the first place, the term ‘musical,' as used in this connection, does not, of course, mean merely ‘used in music! In that case it would only be necessary to enumerate the kinds of sounds so used. On the contrary, many sounds which must be classed with musical sounds are unsuitable for use in music on account of difficulties attending their pro- duction or for some other reason ; and many unmusical sounds are used in music to produce certain effecte, generally of a rhythmioal nature.
